{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2feininger_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280605025/1948080901/0633.xml":{"full_text":"North American Net\nSlightly Below 1947\nIn Second Quarter\nBy Francis P. Douglas\nNorth American Co. today report\ned net Income of $2,562,000, or 30\ncents a common share, for the sec\nond quarter of the year, compared\nwith $2,949,0(10, or 34 cents a share,\na year ago.\nThe company said the decline is\ndue entirely to the company's di\nvestment of holdings in compliance\nwith orders of the Securities and\nExchange Commission. This, thej\ncompany said, transferred earning\npower from the company to its\nstockholders.\nThe quarterly figures exclude any\nearnings from North American\nLight Power Co., the liquidation\nof which is pending. The same is\ntrue of the figures for the 12 months\nending June 30. In that period the\nnet was $12,301,000, equal to $1.43 a\nshare, compared with $16,795,000, or\n$1.96 a share, for the preceding 12\nmonths.\nSavings Loan Reserves Up.\nThe Federal Savings and Loan\nInsurance Corp., in a statement on\noperations for the hscal year ending\nJune 30, said today member associa\ntions\u2019 reserves now stand at $585,\n000,000 as against $181,000,000 in\n1941.\nThe increase in reserves has been\nat a rate substantially above the\nrate in rise of the associations\u2019 as\nsets, according to William H. Hus\nband, general manager of the insur\nance corporation. He also reported\nno insured association has been\nplaced in liquidation by supervising\nauthorities since 1941.\nThe insurance corporation now\nInsures the savings, up to $5,000. of\nnearly 6,000.000 persons in 2,566\nsavings and loan and similar home\nfinancing institutions. Mr. Husband\nsaid.\nThe Home Loan Bank Board also\nreported that the 1,478 Federal\nsavings and loan associations have\ntotal assets of $5,832,000,000, increas\ning their combined resources by 16\nper cent during the last fiscal year.\nAAR Official Promoted.\nE. P. Miller of Mount Rainier.\nMd.. chief clerk of the car service\ndivision of the Association of'\nAmerican Rail\nroads, has been\na p p ointed dis\ntrict manager at\nBoston, A. H.\nOass, division\nchairman, has\nannounced.\nMr. Miller will\nsucceed L. M.\nRoss, who will\nretire August 15.\nStarting his\nrailroad work at\n14, Mr. Miller\njoined the staff\nof the AAR car\nservice division\nMr. Miller.\nearly in World War II.\nDividend payments on common\nstocks listed on the New York Stock\nExchange in the first half year were\n14.4 per cent ahead of the like pe\nriod a year ago, according to the;\nExchange Magazine, but there was\ngreater unevenness of distributions, j\nThis year 371 issues increased pay-\nments w-hile in 1947 the number!\nwas 441.\nPayments were reduced on 82\nequities while only 43 lowered pay- j\nments a year ago. Payments were\nincreased by 45 per cent of the listed\nissues in contrast with 57 per cent\nin the first half of 1947.\nI Business Briefs\nSteel Mill Operations for the cur\nrent week were scheduled at 94.9%\ncapacity, indicating production of\n1,710,500 net tons\u2014American Iron\nA: Steel Institute Figures last week\nwere 94.2% and 1.697,900 tons; a\nmonth ago, 90.8% and 1,636.600; a\nyear ago, 93.2*; and 1,630.900.\nConstruction Employment in July\ntotaled 2,186,000 workers, highest\nmark for the month since 1942, and\ncompared with 2.164.000 in the pre\nvious month and 2,043,000 in the\nsame 1947 month\u2014Bureau of Labor\nStatistics.\nReeve* Brothers, Inc., declared an\nextra dividend of 25 cents and a\nregular quarterly of 25 cents, both\npayable October 1.\nLillv-Tullp Cup Corp. has sold\n*3,000,000 of 4U% cumulative pre\nferred stock at par to Massachu\nsetts Mutual Life and Mutual Ben\nefit Life of Newark. Each took\n15.000 shares.\nGeneral Motors Corp. produced\n186 776 cars and trucks in the United\nStates and Canada in July vs. 164,\n066 in the previous month and 139.\n294 in the same 1947 month. The\nlatest total included 143,195 cars and\n43.581 trucks.\nMathieaon Chemical Corp. con\ncluded an agreement with the WAA\nto purchase a government ammonia\nplant and ammonia oxidation fa-,\ncilities at Lake Charles. La., for a\nreported price of $7,063,300.\nStandard Oil to. or inaiana\nearned $66,179,148 or $4 33 a share\nin six months ended June 30 vs.\n$40,936,430 or $2.68 a year earlier.\nPure Oil Co. profit for six months\nended June 30 was $20,753,000 or\n$4.93 vs. $8,162,000 or $177 in the\nsame 1947 period.\nElectric Power Light Corp. and\nsubsidiaries had net Income of\n*6 651,945 in three months ended\nMay 31. vs. $5,705,512.\nWest Penn Power Co. earned\n$4 632.196 or $1.28 in six months\nended June 30 vs. $4,142,071 or $1.14\na vear earlier\nCnited Light Railways Co. net\nfor 12 months ended June 30 was\n$11,497,947 or *3.25 vs. $10,815,395\nor $3.03 in the preceding fiscal\nperiod\nAmerican Light Traction Co.\nearned $2,527,585 in 12 months\nended June 30 vs. $5,607,316 in the\nprevious year.\nCoca-Cola International Corp. net\nincome for three months ended\nJune 30 was $1,545,602 or $8.22 vs.\n$1,231,857 or $6 34 in the same 1947\nperiod.\nAmerican Locomotive Co. earned\n$2 291,804 or 89 cents in six months\nended June 30 vs. $1,742,454 or 59\ncents a year earlier.\nBucyrus-Erie Co. net for six\nmonths ended June 30 was $2,173,*\n647 or $1.63 vs. $2,256,733 or $1.70 in\nthe same 1947 period.\nFelt Tarraqt Mfg. Co. earned\n$1,214,805 or $2.28 in six months\nended June 30 vs. $655,995 or $1.24\na year earlier.\nSimplicity Pattern Co. profit for\nsix months ended June 30 was\n$653,767 or 88 cents vs. $541,988 or\n\u2019S cents in the same 1947 period.\nEasy Washing Machine Corp.\nearned $1,470,056 or $2.94 in six\nmonths ended June 30_vs. $1,170,075\nor $2.34 a year earlier.'\nStandard Thomson Corp. profit\nfor 12 months ended May 31 was\n$338 453 or 68 cents vs. $842,753 or\n'$1.68 in the previous year.\nN. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE\n3\n2\n6\n1\nJ\n3\n16\n7\n10\n13\nt\n1\n44*\n3144\n20V*\n(furnished *v the\ndales\u2014\nSt