h\nquarter to meet the pressing de\nmands of rank and file consumers.\n\u201cCurrently, allocations account for\nabout 300,000 tons monthly, but indi\ncations are by the fourth quarter\nsuch tonnage will be increased al\nmost half again as much with four\nnew programs nearing the effective\nstate,\u201d Steel said.\n\"At present, allocation of an addi\ntional 160,000 tons monthly is under\ndiscussion, and 10 more programs\nare under preliminary study. Fur\nther, it has been ruled allocations\nmade prior to March 1 under the\npresent law will contniue operative\nuntil September 1, 1949.\u201d\nLast week steel-making operations\nrose one point to 94 per cent of\ncapacity, the equivalent of 1.695,000\ntons, Steel reported. Repairs by Re\npublic Steel Corp. caused a 10.5\npoint drop to 88.5 per cent in the\nCleveland district, and the Wheeling\ndistrict increased 10 points to 92.5.\nChicago Grain\nCHICAGO, Aug. 9 (if;.\u2014Weakness de\nveloped in all commodities deal In or\nthe Board ol Trade today following an\nAgriculture Department forecast of a\nlarger than expected cotton crop.\nThe cotton crop forecast caused\nsharply lower quotations for soybeans and\nlard Traders reasoned that a large pro\nduction. This was seen as influencing\nall fats and oils prices.\nSelling was concentrated in soybeans\nand lard for a time, but then spread to\ngrains. Weakness in cereals was more or\nless in sympathy with other markets\nrather than on any specific new derelop\nment pertaining directly to grains.\nAt noon wheat was '/*-1 y\u00ab lower: Sep\ntember. S2.238'4; corn was lower:\nSeptember, 1.63 Ve; oats were un\nchanged to H lower: September. .7J%: rye\nwas Vi lower: December. S1.70Vg: soy\nbeans were 7V4 to 8 cents lower; Novem\nber *2.65Vi, and lard was 60 to 08\ncents a hundred pound lower; September,:\n*30.42.\nWheat closed 2 to 2Vi lower. Septem\nber. 2.22Vi-2.22; com was 1*4-3% lower.\nSeptember. l.6i%-1.62; oats were %-*t\nlower. September. 72V4-H: rye was 2 to\n2J4 lower. December, 1.69; soybeans were\nPLnPx'\u00ab lower. November. 3.64. and lard\nwas 70 to PO a hundred pounds lower.\nSeptember. 20.05-20.10.\nMarket Averages\nSTOCKS.\nNet change_\nToday noon_\nPrev. day_\nweek ago_\nMonth ago_\nYear ago\n1848 high_\n1948 low_\nPI .9\n98.7\n83.3\nBONDS. 20\nRails.\nNet change \u2014.1\nToday noon 91.5\nPrev. day.. 91.8\nWeek ago 92.1\nMonth ago. 92.6\nYear ago 94.4?\n1948 high 93.\u00bb\n1948 low 87.7\n(Compiled by\n10 10\nIndst. util.\nl unc.\n100.9 99.8\n100.8 99.8\n100.9 100.2\n101.3 101.1\n103.5 105.3\n101.8 102.0\n99.8 98.0\nthe Associated\nlhrn~ frigid\n\u2014.1 unc.\n83.6 108.1\n83.8 108.1\n82.7 108.5\n62.8 109.2\n70.8 116.0\n86.9 110.8\n80 3 107.2\nPresg.f\nForeign Exchange\nNEW YORK. Aug. 9 </P>.\u2014Foreign ex\nhsnse rates follow (Great Britain in\nlollars, others in cental:\nCanadian dollar in New York open\nnarket 7Vs per cent discount or 92.87%\nents, unchanged.\nEurope\u2014Oreat Britain (pound'. *4.03'\u00ab\ninchanged; 30-day futures, 4.03, un\nhanged: 60-day futures, 4.02Va, un\nhanged: 90-day futures, 4.01 H. un\nhanged: France (franc), .33 13/16 of a\nent. unchanged: Italy (Mrs), August,\n\u2018ged rate. ,ool73P: July, .001739:\n(kronai. 27.86. unchanged;\nwedtn\nwltserland~franc) (free).' 25.45, up 703;\nf La tin \"aimer lea\u2014Argentina (frae). 20.89.\nomlnal, up .01 at a cent: Braiil (frae).\n.50. unchanged; Mexico, 14.88, un\nhanged.\nSeiberlint Rubber Co. profit for\nsix months ended June 30 wss $299.\n732 or 59 cents vs. $102,603 or 13;\ncenU in the'iune 1947 period.\nSiffnede Steel Strapping earned\n$543,403 or $138 in six months\nended June 30 vs. $454354 or $1.06\nm year earlier.,\nHigh Building Costs\nExpected to Reduce\nCapital Expenditure\n\u2022y th\u00ab Aiiociatad PrHi\nNEW YORK. Aug. 9.\u2014Under the\ncosts, capital expenditures by in\ndustry in 1949 are expected to fall,\nthe National Industrial Conference\nBoard reports.\nA survey of current business\npractices by the independent re\nsearch organization disclosed a\nmajority of companies anticipated a\ndecline, although some expected\ncapital outlay for 1949 to be about\nthe same as 1949, and a small num\nber ate planning increasing capital\nexpenditures.\nHigh Costs a Handicap.\n\"High construction costs which\nprevail are a severe handicap on\ncontinued expansibn of plant facili\nties.\u201d the board said. \"As a result\nof this spiral, a structure which\ncost $3.20 a square foot to build be\nfore the war will now cost a com\npany $15.20 per square foot\nAnother reason for the declining\nneed for capital expansion is com\npletion of many postwar improve\nment plans started immediately after\nthe war's end.\nMany companies purchased plants\nwhich had been leased from the\nGovernment during and immediately\nafter the war.\nTo finance this expansion, more\nthan 75 per cent of the companies\nuse retained earnings and in second\nplace comes \u201ccurrent depreciation\u201d\nfunds.\n\u201cIn practice,\" the board said,\n\u201cmost companies report they use\na combination of the two methods\nto meet a large proportion of their\ncapital needs.\u201d\nWar Expansion Held Sufficient.\nAbout 5 per cent of the companies\nsaid they financed \"a substantial\npart of their capital needs\" through\nstock or bond issues.\n\u201cThe rearmament program is not\nexpected to increase the capital\nneeds of most of the companies\nsurveyed,\u201d the board said. \"Accord\ning to many of the reporting com\npanies, the expansion which was\ncarried on during the last war\nemergency and the recent postwar\nperiod has been sufficient to take\ncare of any additional production\nwhich might be necessary in the\nnear future.\n\u201cThe general belief Is that a re\narmament program will require\nIncreasing use of second and third\nshifts and stepped-up production\nschedules rather than expansion of\nphysical plant facilities.\u201d\nNew York Produce\nNEW YORK, Aug. 9 t/P).\u2014Butter <2\ndays' receipt*), 842.070; Arm. Whole**!*\npri